3.1 Introduction
Motion is common to everything in the universe.", "fibs": ["Chapter"]}
{"text": "We walk, run and ride a bicycle.", "fibs": ["bicycle"]}
{"text": "Even when we are sleeping, air moves into and out of our lungs and blood flows in arteries and veins.", "fibs": ["air"]}
{"text": "We see leaves falling from trees and water flowing down a dam.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "Automobiles and planes carry people from one place to the other.", "fibs": ["place"]}
{"text": "The earth rotates once every twenty-four hours and revolves round the sun once in a year.", "fibs": ["earth"]}
{"text": "The sun itself is in motion in the Milky Way, which is again moving within its local group of galaxies.", "fibs": ["sun"]}
{"text": "Motion is change in position of an object with time.", "fibs": ["change"]}
{"text": "How does the position change with time ?", "fibs": ["position"]}
{"text": "In this chapter, we shall learn how to describe motion.", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "For this, we develop the concepts of velocity and acceleration.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "We shall confine ourselves to the study of motion of objects along a straight line, also known as rectilinear motion.", "fibs": ["study"]}
{"text": "For the case of rectilinear motion with uniform acceleration, a set of simple equations can be obtained.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Finally, to understand the relative nature of motion, we introduce the concept of relative velocity.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "In our discussions, we shall treat the objects in motion as point objects.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "This approximation is valid so far as the size of the object is much smaller than the distance it moves in a reasonable duration of time.", "fibs": ["approximation"]}
{"text": "In a good number of situations in real-life, the size of objects can be neglected and they can be considered as point-like objects without much error.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "In Kinematics, we study ways to describe motion without going into the causes of motion.", "fibs": ["study"]}
{"text": "What causes motion described in this chapter and the next chapter forms the subject matter of Chapter 5.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "3.2  Position, path length and displacement 

Earlier you learnt that motion is change in position of an object with time.", "fibs": ["Position"]}
{"text": "In order to specify position, we need to use a reference point and a set of axes.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "It is convenient to choose a rectangular coordinate system consisting of three mutually perpenducular axes, labelled  X-, Y-, and Z- axes.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "The point of intersection of these three axes is called origin (O) and serves as the reference point.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "The coordinates (x, y. z) of an object describe the position of the object with respect to this coordinate system.", "fibs": ["x"]}
{"text": "To measure time, we position a clock in this system.", "fibs": ["measure"]}
{"text": "This coordinate system along with a clock constitutes a frame of reference.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "If one or more coordinates of an object change with time, we say that the object is in motion.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "Otherwise, the object is said to be at rest with respect to this frame of reference.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "The choice of a set of axes in a frame of reference depends upon the situation.", "fibs": ["choice"]}
{"text": "For example, for describing motion in one dimension, we need only one axis.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "To describe motion in two/three dimensions, we need a set of two/three axes.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Description of an event depends on the frame of reference chosen for the description.", "fibs": ["event"]}
{"text": "For example, when you say that a car is moving on a road, you are describing the car with respect to a frame of reference attached to you or to the ground.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "But with respect to a frame of reference attached with a person sitting in the car, the car is at rest.", "fibs": ["respect"]}
{"text": "To describe motion along a straight line, we can choose an axis, say X-axis, so that it coincides with the path of the object.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "We then measure the position of the object with reference to a conveniently chosen origin, say O, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["measure"]}
{"text": "Positions to the right of O are taken as positive and to the left of O, as negative.", "fibs": ["right"]}
{"text": "Following this convention, the position coordinates of point P and Q in Fig.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
{"text": "3.1 are +360 m and +240 m. Similarly, the position coordinate of point R is –120 m.

Fig.", "fibs": ["m."]}
{"text": "3.1 x-axis, origin and positions of a car at different times.", "fibs": ["origin"]}
{"text": "Path length
Consider the motion of a car along a straight line.", "fibs": ["length"]}
{"text": "We choose the x-axis such that it coincides with the path of the car’s motion and origin of the axis as the point from where the car started moving, i.e.", "fibs": ["path"]}
{"text": "the car was at x = 0 at t = 0 (Fig.3.1).", "fibs": ["car"]}
{"text": "Let P, Q and R represent the positions of the car at different instants of time.", "fibs": ["P"]}
{"text": "Consider two cases of motion.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "In the first case, the car moves from O to P.  Then the distance moved by the car is OP = +360 m. This distance is called the path length  traversed by the car.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "In the second case, the car moves from O to P and then moves back from P to Q.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "During this course of motion, the path length traversed is OP + PQ = + 360 m + (+120 m) = + 480 m.  Path length is a scalar quantity — a quantity that has a magnitude only and no direction (see Chapter 4).", "fibs": ["course"]}
{"text": "Displacement
It is useful to define another quantity displacement  as  the  change  in position.", "fibs": ["Displacement"]}
{"text": "Let x1 and x2 be the positions of an object at time t1 and t2.", "fibs": ["x1"]}
{"text": "Then its displacement, denoted by ∆x, in time ∆t = (t2 - t1), is given by the difference between the final and initial positions :
 ∆x = x2 – x1
(We use the Greek letter delta (∆) to denote a change in a quantity.)", "fibs": ["displacement"]}
{"text": "If   x2 > x1, ∆x is positive; and if x2 < x1, ∆x is negative.", "fibs": ["x2"]}
{"text": "Displacement has both magnitude and direction.", "fibs": ["Displacement"]}
{"text": "You will read about vectors in the next chapter.", "fibs": ["chapter"]}
{"text": "Presently, we are dealing with motion along a straight line (also called rectilinear motion) only.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "In one-dimensional motion, there are only two directions (backward and forward, upward and downward) in which an object can move, and these two directions can easily be specified by + and – signs.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "For example, displacement of the car in moving from O to P is :
 ∆x = x2 – x1 = (+360 m) – 0 m = +360 m



The displacement has a magnitude of 360 m and is directed in the positive x direction as indicated by the + sign.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Similarly, the displacement of the car from P to Q is 240 m – 360 m = – 120 m. The negative sign indicates the direction of displacement.", "fibs": ["displacement"]}
{"text": "Thus, it is not necessary to use vector notation for discussing motion of objects in one-dimension.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "The magnitude of displacement may or may not be equal to the path length traversed by an object.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "For example, for motion of the car from O to P, the path length is  +360 m and the displacement is +360 m. In this case, the magnitude of displacement (360 m) is equal to the path length (360 m).", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "But consider the motion of the car from O to P and back to Q.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "In this case, the path length = (+360 m) + (+120 m) = + 480 m. However, the displacement = (+240 m) – (0 m) =  + 240 m.  Thus, the magnitude of displacement (240 m) is not equal to the path length (480 m).", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "The magnitude of the displacement for a course of motion may be zero but the corresponding path length is not zero.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "For example, if the car starts from O, goes to P and then returns to O, the final position coincides with the initial position and the displacement is zero.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "However, the path length of this journey is OP + PO = 360 m +  360 m = 720 m.
	Motion of an object can be represented by a position-time graph as you have already learnt about it.", "fibs": ["path"]}
{"text": "Such a graph is a powerful tool to represent and analyse different aspects of motion of an object.", "fibs": ["graph"]}
{"text": "For motion along a straight line, say X-axis, only x-coordinate varies with time and we have an x-t graph.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Let us first consider the simple case in which an object is stationary, e.g.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "a car standing still at x = 40 m.  The position-time graph is a straight line parallel to the time axis, as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["car"]}
