{"text": "3.3  Average velocity and average speed
When an object is in motion, its position changes with time.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "But how fast is the position changing with time and in what direction?", "fibs": ["position"]}
{"text": "To describe this, we define the quantity average velocity.", "fibs": ["quantity"]}
{"text": "Average velocity is defined as the change in position or displacement (∆x) divided by the time intervals (∆t), in which the displacement occurs :
 
(3.1)

where x2  and x1 are the positions of the object at time t2and  t1, respectively.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "Here the bar over the symbol for velocity is a standard notation used to indicate an average quantity.", "fibs": ["bar"]}
{"text": "The SI unit for velocity is m/s or m s–1, although km h–1 is used in many everyday applications.", "fibs": ["SI"]}
{"text": "Like displacement, average velocity is also a vector quantity.", "fibs": ["displacement"]}
{"text": "But as explained earlier, for motion in a straight line, the directional aspect of the vector can be taken care of by + and – signs and we do not have to use the vector notation for velocity in this chapter.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
