{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "3.5 Position-time graph for an object (a) moving with positive velocity, (b) moving with negative velocity, and (c) at rest.", "fibs": ["graph"]}
{"text": "Average velocity as defined above involves only the displacement of the object.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "We have seen earlier that the magnitude of displacement may be different from the actual path length.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "To describe the rate of motion over the actual path, we introduce another quantity called average speed.", "fibs": ["rate"]}
{"text": "Average speed is defined as the total path length travelled divided by the total time interval during which the motion has taken place :
 
(3.2)

Average speed has obviously the same unit       (m s–1) as that of velocity.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "But it does not tell us in what direction an object is moving.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "Thus, it is always positive (in contrast to the average velocity which can be positive or negative).", "fibs": ["contrast"]}
{"text": "If the motion of an object is along a straight line and in the same direction, the magnitude of displacement is equal to the total path length.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "In that case, the magnitude of average velocity is equal to the average speed.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "This is not always the case, as you will see in the following example.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Example 3.1 A car is moving along a straight line, say OP in Fig.", "fibs": ["Example"]}
{"text": "It moves from O to P in 18 s and returns from P to Q in 6.0 s.  What are the average velocity and average speed of the car in going (a) from O to P ?", "fibs": ["P"]}
{"text": "and (b) from O to P and back to Q ?", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "Answer  (a)
 
 
 
  
Thus, in this case the average speed is equal to the magnitude of the average velocity.", "fibs": ["Answer"]}
{"text": "(b) In this case,
Thus, in this case the average speed is not equal to the magnitude of the average velocity.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "This happens because the motion here involves change in direction so that the path length is greater than the magnitude of displacement.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "This shows that speed is, in general, greater than the magnitude of the velocity.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "If the car in Example 3.1 moves from O to P and comes back to O in the same time interval, average speed is 20 m/s but the average velocity is zero !", "fibs": ["car"]}
