{"text": "An object is said to be in motion if its position changes with time.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "The position of the object can be specified with reference to a conveniently chosen origin.", "fibs": ["position"]}
{"text": "For motion in a straight line, position to the right of the origin is taken as positive and to the left as negative.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Path length is defined as the total length of the path traversed by an object.", "fibs": ["length"]}
{"text": "Displacement is the change in position : ∆x  =  x2 – x1.", "fibs": ["Displacement"]}
{"text": "Path length is greater or equal to the magnitude of the displacement between the same points.", "fibs": ["length"]}
{"text": "An object is said to be in uniform motion in a straight line if its displacement is  equal in equal intervals of time.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "Otherwise, the motion is said to be non-uniform.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Average velocity is the displacement divided by the time interval in which the displacement occurs :
 
 On an x-t graph, the average velocity over a time interval is the slope of the line connecting the initial and final positions corresponding to that interval.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "Average Speed is the ratio of total path length traversed and the corresponding time interval.", "fibs": ["Speed"]}
{"text": "The average speed of an object is greater or equal to the magnitude of the average velocity over a given time interval.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "Instantaneous velocity or simply velocity is defined as the limit of the average velocity as the time interval ∆t becomes infinitesimally small : 
 
	The velocity at a particular instant is equal to the slope of the tangent drawn on         position-time graph at that instant.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "Average acceleration is the change in velocity divided by the time interval during which the change occurs :
 
9.", "fibs": ["acceleration"]}
{"text": "Instantaneous acceleration is defined as the limit of the average acceleration as the time interval ∆t goes to zero :
 
	The acceleration of an object at a particular time is the slope of the velocity-time graph at that instant of time.", "fibs": ["acceleration"]}
{"text": "For uniform motion, acceleration is zero and the x-t graph is a straight line inclined to the time axis and the v-t graph is a straight line parallel to the time axis.", "fibs": ["uniform"]}
{"text": "For motion with uniform acceleration, x-t graph is a parabola while the v-t graph is a straight line inclined to the time axis.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "The area under the velocity-time curve between times t1 and t2 is equal to the displacement of the object during that interval of time.", "fibs": ["area"]}
{"text": "For objects in uniformly accelerated rectilinear motion, the five quantities, displacement x, time taken t, initial velocity v0, final velocity v and acceleration a are related by a set of simple equations called kinematic equations of motion :
					        v = v0 +  at
 
 
	if the position of the object at time t = 0 is 0.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "If the particle starts at x = x0 , x in above equations is replaced by (x – x0).", "fibs": ["particle"]}
{"text": "The path length traversed by an object between two points is, in general, not the same as the magnitude of displacement.", "fibs": ["path"]}
{"text": "The displacement depends only on the end points; the path length (as the name implies) depends on the actual path.", "fibs": ["displacement"]}
{"text": "In one dimension, the two quantities are equal only if the object does not change its direction during the course of motion.", "fibs": ["dimension"]}
{"text": "In all other cases, the path length is greater than the magnitude of displacement.", "fibs": ["path"]}
{"text": "In view of point 1 above, the average speed of an object is greater than or equal to the magnitude of the average velocity over a given time interval.", "fibs": ["view"]}
{"text": "The two are equal only if the path length is equal to the magnitude of displacement.", "fibs": ["path"]}
{"text": "The origin and the positive direction of an axis are a matter of choice.", "fibs": ["origin"]}
{"text": "You should first specify this choice before you assign signs to quantities like displacement, velocity and acceleration.", "fibs": ["choice"]}
{"text": "If a particle is speeding up, acceleration is in the direction of velocity; if its speed is decreasing, acceleration is in the direction opposite to that of the velocity.", "fibs": ["particle"]}
{"text": "This statement is independent of the choice of the origin and the axis.", "fibs": ["statement"]}
{"text": "The sign of acceleration does not tell us whether the particle’s speed is increasing or decreasing.", "fibs": ["sign"]}
{"text": "The sign of acceleration (as mentioned in point 3) depends on the choice of the positive direction of the axis.", "fibs": ["sign"]}
{"text": "For example, if the vertically upward direction is chosen to be the positive direction of the axis, the acceleration due to gravity is negative.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "If a particle is falling under gravity, this acceleration, though negative, results in increase in speed.", "fibs": ["particle"]}
{"text": "For a particle thrown upward, the same negative acceleration (of gravity) results in decrease in speed.", "fibs": ["particle"]}
{"text": "The zero velocity of a particle at any instant does not necessarily imply zero acceleration at that instant.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "A particle may be momentarily at rest and yet have non-zero acceleration.", "fibs": ["particle"]}
{"text": "For example, a particle thrown up has zero velocity at its uppermost point but the acceleration at that instant continues to be the acceleration due to gravity.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "In the kinematic equations of motion [Eq.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "The equations are applicable in all situations (for one dimensional motion with constant acceleration) provided the values of different quantities are substituted in the equations with proper signs.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "The definitions of instantaneous velocity and acceleration (Eqs.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "(3.3) and (3.5)) are exact and are always correct while the kinematic equations (Eq.", "fibs": ["Eq."]}
{"text": "(3.11)) are true only for motion in which the magnitude and the direction of acceleration are constant during the course of motion.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
